{
  "analysis": "Nginx (port 80) and websockify (port 6080) are running. The unattended floppy image exists and contains WINNT.SIF with the correct product key and tb-admin account creation commands. QEMU is failing to start because VNC port 5901 is already in use by an unknown process, and lsof/fuser did not reveal the owning PID. We need to identify and kill the process holding port 5901, then start QEMU with VNC :1 and the floppy attached. After starting QEMU, verify that QEMU owns port 5901, the process is running, and there are no errors in the log.",
  "plan": "1) Find the inode(s) for the TCP listeners on port 5901 using /proc/net/tcp and /proc/net/tcp6. 2) Map the inode(s) to the owning PID(s) by scanning /proc/*/fd symlinks, then kill those PIDs to free port 5901. 3) Verify that port 5901 is free. 4) Start QEMU with the ISO, qcow2 disk, and floppy image, with VNC bound to 0.0.0.0:1 (port 5901). 5) Verify QEMU is running, confirm ports, and tail the log for any startup errors.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "INODE4=$(awk 'BEGIN{t=\"170D\"} NR>1{split($2,a,\":\"); if (a[2]==t && $4==\"0A\") print $10}' /proc/net/tcp); INODE6=$(awk 'BEGIN{t=\"170D\"} NR>1{split($2,a,\":\"); if (a[2]==t && $4==\"0A\") print $10}' /proc/net/tcp6); echo \"Inodes on 5901: IPv4=$INODE4 IPv6=$INODE6\"\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "PIDS=\"\"; for pid in /proc/[0-9]*; do for inode in $INODE4 $INODE6; do [ -n \"$inode\" ] || continue; ls -l \"$pid\"/fd 2>/dev/null | grep -q \"socket:\\[$inode\\]\" && PIDS=\"$PIDS ${pid##*/}\"; done; done; echo \"PIDs holding 5901:$PIDS\"\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "if [ -n \"$PIDS\" ]; then echo \"Killing: $PIDS\"; kill -9 $PIDS || true; sleep 1; fi\n",
      "duration": 1.0
